[
    {
        "content": "<p>I created the following definition of a triangle number by modifying the definitions of <code>Odd</code> and <code>Even</code>.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Triangle</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I don't know how to correctly read this.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>I know that <code>def Triangle</code> creates a definition of a thing called <code>Triangle</code></li>\n<li>I know that the round brackets mean anyone using this definition must provide a parameter <code>a</code></li>\n<li>In place of <code>Prop</code> I am used to seeing a proof objective / lemma proposal</li>\n<li>Is <code>Prop</code> saying that this is a placeholder for anything that can be an instance of <code>Prop</code> (the universe)? I would have expected something like <code>P : Prop</code> to say <code>P</code> in the universe of Propositions.</li>\n<li>And why does the actual definition look like a proof justification by being after <code>:=</code> ?</li>\n<li><code>dsimp</code> support seems to work without me doing anything - I can see the unfolded definition in the infoview with the following example:</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Triangle</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Triangle</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">dsimp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Triangle</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">---- &lt; --- seems to work without me doing anything</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">use</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">4</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 483595573,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1732149056
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does it help if you compare to the following?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">double</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>this should help dispell you of the notion that <code>:=</code> is just for \"proof justifications\"</p>",
        "id": 483598239,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1732150686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>hi Eric - sadly ive not come across that pattern either.</p>\n<p>of course I can work out what it should mean, but not how to read it precisely and correctly</p>",
        "id": 483598535,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1732150903
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So the pattern is</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">SomeName</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">term1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">SomeType</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hyp2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">AnotherType</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">TypeOfSomeName</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">theTerm</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Of</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">thatType</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 483620155,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1732166942
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>After the name, you get</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A list of assumptions/hypotheses/variables/parameters.</li>\n<li>Then a <code>:</code>.</li>\n<li>Then a type <code>T</code>.</li>\n<li>Then <code>:=</code>.</li>\n<li>Then a term <code>t</code>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 483620190,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1732166985
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And <code>t</code> should have type <code>T</code>. Otherwise Lean will complain.</p>",
        "id": 483620274,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1732167043
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In your example about triangle numbers, you are defining a property of the natural number <code>a</code>, and you are calling that property <code>Triangle</code>. The property is <code>∃ n, 2 * a = n * (n + 1)</code>, which is going to be the <code>t</code> in the list above. And it correctly has type <code>Prop</code>.</p>",
        "id": 483620435,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1732167182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks Johan - that is helping.</p>\n<p>I will now apply that pattern to the more familiar code:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">linarith</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>so </p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>a+1=6</code> is a <strong>type</strong> of <code>Proposition</code></li>\n<li><code>by linarith</code> is a <strong>term</strong> of the <strong>type</strong> <code>Proposition</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Is that correct?</p>\n<p>Does that mean all the beginner small proofs I've been looking at have a \"proof objective\" as a type <code>Prop</code> and a proof which is a term of that type <code>Prop</code></p>\n<hr>\n<p>Going back to the original example:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Triangle</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Is it normal for the \"type <code>T</code>\" to be a generic <code>Prop</code> and not something \"instantiated\". This is what triggered my confusion, that it looks \"uninstantiated\" unlike say <code>a+1=6</code>.</p>\n<p>Would we ever have something like:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Thing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">something</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>where <code>Nat</code> is the type <code>T</code> in the pattern?</p>\n<hr>\n<p>I'm looking again at the diagram I drew a few weeks back to help make sense of this:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/uU6J_253433uIQRZLSUn8FX3/app_taxonomy.png\">app_taxonomy.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/uU6J_253433uIQRZLSUn8FX3/app_taxonomy.png\" title=\"app_taxonomy.png\"><img data-original-dimensions=\"2364x1182\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/uU6J_253433uIQRZLSUn8FX3/app_taxonomy.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 483687798,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1732193321
    },
    {
        "content": "<hr>\n<p>I tried to answer my own question but the follows fails:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Thing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- &lt; -- doesn't complain</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Thing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">4</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">norm_num</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- &lt; -- fails</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 483688736,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1732193589
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i suspect <code>norm_num</code> doesn't have the ability to see through definitions, which is causing this to fail.</p>",
        "id": 483688863,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732193639
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if you use <code>by rw [Thing]; norm_num</code>, the proof should succeed.</p>",
        "id": 483689008,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732193673
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks Edward - and the main question is that the <code>def Thing</code> is ok with an apparently uninstantiated <code>Nat</code> as the <code>type T</code> ?</p>",
        "id": 483689209,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1732193738
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>how do you mean \"uninstantiated\"?</p>",
        "id": 483689738,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732193881
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>in this case, the part after <code>:=</code> clearly gives an instance/value of <code>Nat</code>, namely <code>a * 2</code>?</p>",
        "id": 483690196,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732194019
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"724904\">rzeta0</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/interpreting.20.60Prop.60.20in.20.60def.60/near/483689209\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thanks Edward - and the main question is that the <code>def Thing</code> is ok with an apparently uninstantiated <code>Nat</code> as the <code>type T</code> ?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Not sure if this helps, but a value <code>h</code> whose type is <code>∃ n, 2 * a = n * (n + 1)</code> is a proof of the proposition <code>∃ n, 2 * a = n * (n + 1)</code>. But <code>∃ n, 2 * a = n * (n + 1)</code> itself has a type (because everything does), and its type is <code>Prop</code> (for \"proposition\").</p>\n<p>Although everything has a type, not everything <em>is</em> a type, though: If <code>a</code> is a natural number, the natural number <code>a * 2</code> is not a type, so you can't write it <code>def Thing (a : ℕ) : a * 2 := sorry</code>. That is, you're not \"specifying\" a term twice when defining <code>Thing</code>, but rather you're specifying a type and a term (and sometimes terms can also be types, but not in the case of a specific natural number).</p>",
        "id": 483690610,
        "sender_full_name": "Mauricio Collares",
        "timestamp": 1732194146
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"724904\">rzeta0</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/interpreting.20.60Prop.60.20in.20.60def.60/near/483687798\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>so</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>a+1=6</code> is a <strong>type</strong> of <code>Proposition</code></li>\n<li><code>by linarith</code> is a <strong>term</strong> of the <strong>type</strong> <code>Proposition</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Is that correct?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>in a way, this is correct. here's how i'd formulate it:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>a + 1 = 6</code> is a <strong>term</strong> of the <strong>type</strong> <code>Prop</code></li>\n<li><code>by linarith</code> is* a <strong>term</strong> of the <strong>type</strong> <code>a + 1 = 6</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>(*) technically, <code>by linarith</code> does some magic to become a term, but that's not that important</p>",
        "id": 483691067,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732194283
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that (the term produced by) <code>by linarith</code> has type <code>a+1=6</code>, not <code>Prop</code>.</p>",
        "id": 483691631,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1732194462
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"684366\">Edward van de Meent</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/interpreting.20.60Prop.60.20in.20.60def.60/near/483691067\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>in a way, this is correct. here's how i'd formulate it:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>a + 1 = 6</code> is a <strong>term</strong> of the <strong>type</strong> <code>Prop</code></li>\n<li><code>by linarith</code> is* a <strong>term</strong> of the <strong>type</strong> <code>a + 1 = 6</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>(*) technically, <code>by linarith</code> does some magic to become a term, but that's not that important</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>We're almost there - all this is very helpful!</p>\n<p>What I remain confused about is when you say: <code>a + 1 = 6</code> is a <strong>term</strong> of the <strong>type</strong> <code>Prop</code>.</p>\n<p>In the pattern above the bit before the <code>:=</code> is a type.  So I can now see how <code>Nat</code> is a Type. But I can't see how <code>a +1 = 6</code> is a type.</p>\n<p>Actually, looking at that diagram again, of course <code>a + 1 = 6</code> is a proposition, and so is a <code>Prop</code> type.</p>\n<p>I think the RHS of that diagram is still not deeply settled in my mind yet!</p>",
        "id": 483694173,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1732195259
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>a +1 = 6</code> is a type, in that terms of that type are proofs that it is true, and the statement is true exactly when there is an element of the type.</p>",
        "id": 483695263,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732195589
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i guess it is confusing to call <code>a + 1 = 6</code> a type when <code>a + 1 = 6 : Type</code> is <em>not</em> correct. something can also be called a type when it appears on the RHS of a type judgement <code>t:T</code>. in this way, propositions (terms <code>p</code> with <code>p:Prop</code>) are a special kind of type. to distinguish between thise, it might be worthwile to call such <code>p</code> <em>propositional</em> types, while terms <code>t</code> with <code>t:Type u</code> can be called <em>true</em> types.</p>",
        "id": 483697720,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732196267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Calling everything a \"sort\" is the way out</p>",
        "id": 483698100,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1732196390
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But colloquially, I think \"type\" is often used to mean <code>Sort _</code>, and when we actually mean <code>Type</code> then we write it as such</p>",
        "id": 483698229,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1732196420
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(<code>Sort _</code> is a lean way of saying either <code>Prop</code> or <code>Type _</code>).<br>\nIn this way, replacing \"type\" with \"sort\" in the following might clear it up.</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"112680\">Johan Commelin</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/interpreting.20.60Prop.60.20in.20.60def.60/near/483620190\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>After the name, you get</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A list of assumptions/hypotheses/variables/parameters.</li>\n<li>Then a <code>:</code>.</li>\n<li>Then a type <code>T</code>.</li>\n<li>Then <code>:=</code>.</li>\n<li>Then a term <code>t</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 483698855,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732196608
    },
    {
