    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"310045\">Eric Wieser</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/.E2.9C.94.20interpreting.20.60Prop.60.20in.20.60def.60/near/483598239\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Does it help if you compare to the following?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">double</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>this should help dispell you of the notion that <code>:=</code> is just for \"proof justifications\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I haven't learned about <strong>functions</strong> yet, but is this <code>double</code> different to what I might learn later about functions?</p>",
        "id": 484090320,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1732390798
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think it's special at least. It's one of a few ways to define such a function, with not too much variation as to how you would write it</p>",
        "id": 484091465,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1732391826
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You might come across <code>def double : Nat -&gt; Nat := fun a =&gt; 2 * a</code>, but that's pretty much the same thing, and in most cases the only reason the first version might be preferred is that it's shorter to type. They do the same thing though. (Forgive my non-unicode spelling, I'm away from my pc atm)</p>",
